h, Spanish, English, Tahitian, and Uvean, ranging from literature to songs and paintings. She shows how Pacific nuclear survivors’ stories reveal an alternative vision of the apocalypse: instead of promoting individualism and survivalism, they advocate mutual assistance, cultural resilience, South-South transnational solidarities, and Indigenous women’s leadership. Drawing upon their experience resisting both nuclear colonialism and carbon imperialism, Pacific storytellers offer compelling narratives to nurture the land and each other in times of global environmental collapse.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aClimatic changes in literature. 0aEcocriticism in literature. 0aNuclear energy in literature. 0aPacific Island literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aPacific Island literaturexThemes, motives. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Subjects & Themes / Nature .2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478059059?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478059059423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478059059/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles